= Chapter 8: Structure of Woody Plants

== Introduction to Secondary Growth

- *Secondary growth* increases the width (girth) of stems and roots, distinct from primary growth which increases length.
- It is characteristic of *woody plants* (all gymnosperms and many angiosperms, specifically eudicots and magnoliids).
- *Secondary tissues* are produced by lateral meristems: the *vascular cambium* and the *cork cambium*.
- *Wood* is technically *secondary xylem*.
- *Bark* includes all tissues external to the vascular cambium, including *secondary phloem* and *periderm*.
- Advantages of secondary growth include increased conduction capacity (more xylem and phloem) and mechanical support (more fibers and thick-walled cells), allowing plants to grow taller and larger.
- Disadvantages include the high energy cost of constructing and maintaining a large woody body and the need for greater defenses against pathogens and pests.
- #figure(
    image(images.at("8-1").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("8-1").caption
  )
- In young stems, a *fascicular cambium* arises from undifferentiated procambium within vascular bundles, and an *interfascicular cambium* develops from parenchyma cells between bundles.
- #figure(
    image(images.at("8-2").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("8-2").caption
  )
- These two cambia connect to form a continuous cylinder, the *vascular cambium*.
- #figure(
    image(images.at("8-3").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("8-3").caption
  )

== The Vascular Cambium

- The *vascular cambium* is a simple meristem consisting of a single layer of meristematic cells.
- It contains two types of cells: *fusiform initials* and *ray initials*.
- *Fusiform initials* are long, vertically oriented cells that produce the *axial system* of the secondary vascular tissues (tracheids, vessel elements, fibers, and axial parenchyma).
- #figure(
    image(images.at("8-4").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("8-4").caption
  )
- *Ray initials* are short, horizontally oriented cells that produce the *radial system* (vascular rays), composed mainly of ray parenchyma cells.
- #figure(
    image(images.at("8-5").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("8-5").caption
  )
- Cell division in the cambium can be *periclinal* (parallel to the surface) or *anticlinal* (perpendicular to the surface).
- *Periclinal divisions* produce secondary xylem to the inside and secondary phloem to the outside.
- #figure(
    image(images.at("8-6").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("8-6").caption
  )
- *Anticlinal divisions* increase the circumference of the vascular cambium to accommodate the increasing diameter of the xylem core.
- If fusiform initials are aligned in horizontal rows, the cambium is *storied*; if not, it is *nonstoried*.
- #figure(
    image(images.at("8-7").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("8-7").caption
  )

== Secondary Xylem (Wood)

- The *axial system* conducts water and minerals vertically and provides mechanical strength.
- The *radial system* (rays) transports carbohydrates from the phloem into the wood for storage or use and moves water laterally.
- #figure(
    image(images.at("8-8").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("8-8").caption
  )
- #figure(
    image(images.at("8-9").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("8-9").caption
  )
- *Gymnosperm wood* (softwood) is simpler, consisting mainly of *tracheids* in the axial system and narrow rays. It lacks vessels and usually lacks fibers.
- #figure(
    image(images.at("8-10").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("8-10").caption
  )
- *Angiosperm wood* (hardwood) is more complex, containing *vessel elements*, *tracheids*, *fibers*, and *axial parenchyma*.
- #figure(
    image(images.at("8-11").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("8-11").caption
  )
- *Growth rings* (annual rings) form due to differential growth rates during the season.
- *Early wood* (spring wood) has large cells with thin walls to maximize water conduction when water is abundant.
- *Late wood* (summer wood) has smaller cells with thicker walls to provide strength when water is scarce.
- In *ring porous* wood, vessels in early wood are much larger than in late wood.
- #figure(
    image(images.at("8-13").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("8-13").caption
  )
- In *diffuse porous* wood, vessels are of similar size throughout the growth ring.
- #figure(
    image(images.at("8-12").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("8-12").caption
  )
- #figure(
    image(images.at("8-14").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("8-14").caption
  )
- *Sapwood* is the outer, living, physiologically active wood involved in conduction and storage.
- *Heartwood* is the inner, dead, non-conducting wood. It provides structural support and is often darker due to the accumulation of resins, tannins, and other compounds.
- *Tyloses* are balloon-like outgrowths of parenchyma cells that block vessels in heartwood, preventing the spread of pathogens.
- #figure(
    image(images.at("B8-1").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("B8-1").caption
  )
- #figure(
    image(images.at("B8-2").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("B8-2").caption
  )
- #figure(
    image(images.at("B8-3").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("B8-3").caption
  )
- *Reaction wood* forms in response to gravity to correct the orientation of leaning stems or branches.
    - *Compression wood* forms on the lower side of leaning stems in conifers (enriched with lignin).
    - *Tension wood* forms on the upper side of leaning stems in angiosperms (enriched with cellulose, often forming gelatinous fibers).
- Variations in wood structure are used for identification.
